## Question 4: Titanic Dataset Analysis
```{r}
# Import dataset
mydata = read_excel("MSBA_Datafile.xlsx", sheet = "Set A")
head(mydata)
```

```{r}
# Prepare Titanic data
titanic = mydata
titanic$Survived = factor(titanic$Survived, labels = c("No", "Yes"))
titanic$Pclass = factor(titanic$Pclass, labels = c("1st", "2nd", "3rd"))
```

### Q4(a) - Survival by Ticket Class

```{r}
# Visualize Survival by Ticket Class
ggplot(titanic, aes(x=Pclass, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_bar(position="dodge") +
  labs(title="Survival Status by Ticket Class",
       x="Ticket Class", y="Count", fill="Survived") +
  theme_minimal()
```

**Interpretation:** First class passengers had a higher survival rate compared to second and third class. Third class passengers had the highest death count, suggesting socio-economic status played a role in survival chances.

### Q4(b) - Survival by Gender

```{r}
# Visualize Survival by Gender
ggplot(titanic, aes(x=Sex, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_bar(position="dodge") +
  labs(title="Survival Status by Gender",
       x="Gender", y="Count", fill="Survived") +
  theme_minimal()
```

**Interpretation:** Females had a significantly higher survival rate than males. This aligns with the "women and children first" evacuation protocol followed during the Titanic disaster.

### Q4(c) - Cluster Analysis

```{r}
# Prepare data for clustering - use Survived, Pclass, Sex, Age
titanic_cluster = mydata[, c("Survived", "Pclass", "Sex", "Age")]

# Encode Sex as numeric
titanic_cluster$Sex = ifelse(titanic_cluster$Sex == "male", 1, 0)

# Remove missing values
titanic_cluster = na.omit(titanic_cluster)

# Normalize
z = titanic_cluster
means = apply(z, 2, mean)
sds = apply(z, 2, sd)
nor = scale(z, center=means, scale=sds)

# Euclidean distance
distance = dist(nor)

# Hierarchical clustering - complete linkage
mydata.hclust = hclust(distance)
plot(mydata.hclust, hang=-1, main="Hierarchical Clustering - Titanic")
```

```{r}
# Hierarchical clustering - average linkage
mydata.hclusta = hclust(distance, method="average")
plot(mydata.hclusta, hang=-1, main="Hierarchical Clustering (Average) - Titanic")
```

```{r}
# Cluster membership - 3 clusters
member.c = cutree(mydata.hclust, 3)
member.a = cutree(mydata.hclusta, 3)
table(member.c, member.a)
```

```{r}
# Cluster means (normalized)
aggregate(nor, list(member.c), mean)
```

```{r}
# Cluster means (original scale)
aggregate(titanic_cluster, list(member.c), mean)
```

```{r}
# Silhouette plot
plot(silhouette(cutree(mydata.hclust, 3), distance))
```

```{r}
# Scree plot - WSS
wss = (nrow(nor)-1)*sum(apply(nor, 2, var))
for (i in 2:10) wss[i] = sum(kmeans(nor, centers=i)$withinss)
plot(1:10, wss, type="b", xlab="Number of Clusters", ylab="Within groups sum of squares",
     main="Scree Plot - Optimal Clusters")
```

```{r}
# K-means clustering with 3 clusters
set.seed(123)
kc = kmeans(nor, 3)
kc
```

```{r}
# Plot clusters
plot(Survived ~ Age, titanic_cluster, col=kc$cluster,
     main="K-means Clusters: Survived vs Age")
```

**Interpretation:** The cluster analysis groups Titanic passengers into 3 distinct clusters based on survival, class, gender, and age. Cluster means reveal that one cluster likely represents young female survivors from higher classes, another represents male non-survivors from lower classes, and a third represents a mixed middle group. The silhouette plot and scree plot help confirm that 3 clusters provide a reasonable segmentation of the passengers.

